## Thread.Abort Migration → .NET 8

### Pattern Analysis

Your code has **three** patterns that need migration:

| Location | Pattern | Replacement |
|----------|---------|-------------|
| `Stop()` → `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | ThreadAbortException as control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | ResetAbort to continue execution | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — migrated from ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we control the loop via the token.
                // Loop condition will exit naturally on next iteration.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

1. **`volatile bool _running` → `CancellationTokenSource`** — The token is thread-safe by design and can interrupt blocking calls. The bool could not.

2. **`Thread.Abort()` → `_cts.Cancel()`** — `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. Cooperative cancellation replaces it.

3. **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` → `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (...)`** — The `when` guard ensures you only catch cancellation you initiated, not unrelated `OperationCanceledException`s from other sources.

4. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed** — No equivalent needed. The loop condition `!token.IsCancellationRequested` controls whether the thread continues.

5. **`Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))`** — Sleep blindly waits; `Join` actually waits for the thread to finish and returns early if it does.

6. **`IDisposable` added** — `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`. Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks.

### Critical Pitfall: `GetNextItem()` Must Cooperate

Your original comment says `GetNextItem()` "may block." **This is the most important part of the migration.** If `GetNextItem` blocks on a synchronous call that doesn't accept a `CancellationToken`, cancellation will stall until it returns. You must update it:

```csharp
// ❌ Before — blocks indefinitely, cannot be cancelled
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take()
}

// ✅ After — unblocks when token is cancelled
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If `GetNextItem` uses `Thread.Sleep`, `WaitOne`, or similar:

```csharp
// ❌ Thread.Sleep — ignores cancellation
Thread.Sleep(5000);

// ✅ Token-aware wait — wakes immediately on cancel
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000);
```

### Validation Checklist

- ✅ No `Thread.Abort` references remain
- ✅ No `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks remain
- ✅ No `Thread.ResetAbort` calls remain
- ✅ `CancellationToken` passed through the full call chain
- ✅ `CancellationTokenSource` is disposed
- ✅ Cleanup logic (rollback) preserved in `OperationCanceledException` handler
